	An investment bank based abroad recently got in touch with the Mumbai-based head of a forensic practice. The banker wanted to run a back-ground check on some Indian promoters looking to raise capital abroad. Since the offer was underwritten, the bankers wanted to make sure everything about the company and its promoters was above-board.&#13;
&#13;
	Such an instance of investment bankers requiring reputational and forensic due diligence on promoters in such cases is not unusual. In fact, it is part of a global trend which is now showing up in India too, according to experts, with evidence of this being seen by practitioners including Kroll Advisory, KPMG, EY and PWC.&#13;
&#13;
	At the root of such decisions is the fact that many offers are underwritten, which means that the banker offers to pick up the securities in an offer if they remain unsold. This can creates a large financial liability for the banker if the issue goes awry.“Investment bankers are using various means to get comfortable on capital raises etc…I am seeing the first signs of some specific procedures that are in the nature of forensic checks being requested for being incorporated as part of the diligence process,” said Sandeep Dhupia - Head, Forensic Services at KPMG in India.&#13;
&#13;
	“It has picked up over the last 12 months as the economy has begun to look better. There are queries from both investment banks handling foreign capital-raising, as well as those looking at strategic investments into India. Sectors in which this has been seen include defence, insurance, pharma and consumer goods,” said Reshmi Khurana, Managing Director and Country Head Operations for Kroll Advisory&#13;
&#13;
	 “Raising capital overseas has increased in the last few years due to lower costs and lesser paperwork and for a while now, forensic has been assisting capital raising activities not just in the domestic market but also abroad; forensic experts assist in reviewing the books and in conducting integrity checks on promoters/C suite. Given that their money is at stake, such reviews have become the need of the hour for the I-Bankers,” said Dinesh Anand, Leader- Forensics, PwC India on the topic.ALSO READ: UCX promoter Ketan Sheth siphoned funds, finds KPMG forensic auditThe use of forensic services in India have largely been seen to be employed by private equity players or to banks faced with bad loans. The latter may want to find out if their money has been siphoned off by the promoters.&#13;
&#13;
	&#13;
	The former want to make sure that their investment will be in safe hands. Investment bankers too face similar risk exposure and wish to run qualitative and quantitative checks on the person or company with whom business is being done.&#13;
&#13;
	"Sometimes, in IPO situations, the underwriter who takes the exposure may appoint a firm to conduct a reputational due diligence. This includes background checks covering the company, it’s Directors and key management personnel. Such due diligence can also include searching for unknown related parties, looking into significant transactions with such related parties, whether a key related party is in financial distress or has large loans backed by corporate guarantees and if there have been regulatory issues associated with the parties involved,” said Dhruv Phophalia, Managing Director with Alvarez &amp; Marsal, leading the firm’s Global Forensic and Dispute Services practice in India.&#13;
&#13;
	“India’s positive business environment has drawn the interest of global investment banks, however they are increasingly aware of the risks prevalent...background checks involve understanding the integrity and credibility of the individual to identify any red flags or dubious connections. We also see a trend in i-bankers becoming increasingly aware of requirements in relation to complying with international sanctions lists,” said Arpinder Singh, Partner and National Leader, Fraud Investigation &amp; Dispute Services. &#13;
&#13;
	The problem is investment bankers often have to balance both their need for safety which requires allowing forensic auditors to get to the bottom of any possible issues; while at the same time not getting on the wrong side of the senior management or promoters.&#13;
&#13;
	“What is missing though, and not unique to this particular type of fund raising, is the post facto checks and balances to confirm use of monies in the manner expected. With defaults in redemptions increasing, this is slowly coming to limelight and gaining significant traction,” said Dinesh Anand, of PwC India.&#13;
					Playing Safe&#13;
			&#13;
					* Foreign i-bankers are now conducting forensic and reputational due diligence on promoters coming to them for capital raising abroad&#13;
			&#13;
					* Bankers helping with a public offering may have to buy unsold securities in underwritten issues&#13;
			&#13;
					* Investment bankers are also seeking such due-diligence on Indian promoters on behalf of foreign strategic investors&#13;
			&#13;
					* Sectors where this has happened include defence, insurance, pharma, consumer goods&#13;
			&#13;
					* Firms say such checks have picked up over last 12 months with improving economic sentiment&#13;
			&#13;

