Dish TV has lost 8 per cent over the last three trading sessions on concerns that aggressive promotions by DTH rivals would lead to a fresh pricing war impacting its average revenue per user (ARPU).&#13;
Dish TV has lost 8 per cent over the last three trading sessions on concerns that aggressive promotions by DTH rivals would lead to a fresh pricing war impacting its average revenue per user (ARPU).Recently, Tata Sky had launched a recharge of Rs 8 a day for single day access. Given the fixed costs, the move, which may result in subscribers opting for the service only for a part of the month, will impact Dish TV's leverage and margins.Given the offer seems to be targeted at the semi urban and rural markets, this could impact Dish TV as it has large subscriber base in these markets. Phase III and Phase IV compulsory digitisation is in the semi urban markets and are scheduled to be implemented by December 2015 and December 2016.Dish TV management has, however, said the move by its rival will not affect it. R C Venkateish, Chief Executive Officer, says that from a new customer acquisition perspective, there is zero impact as a customer who will pay Rs 8 once in a while is not going to pay Rs 2,000 upfront. “As far as new customers are concerned those on Dish platform won’t be impacted. Tata Sky is downgrading its own customers, which is why this is a self goal.”Tata Sky is looking at tapping the rural base further with this low denomination recharge which will enable the DTH subscriber the flexibility to pay for days of use rather than a monthly subscription where the service may not be availed on a daily basis.Dish TV, on the other hand, has been customising its content for regional audiences with its brand Zing. The Tata Sky move, according to analysts, could also be a move to counter the success of Zing. While Tata Sky move could impact other players, analysts say the key worry would be if the recharge war is to escalate to one on the set top box. This is the largest upfront cost (Rs 1,700-Rs 2,000) that customers make when they subscribe to one of the direct to home services.In the near term, the Street will also look to the operational performance in the March quarter where the company is expected to post strong net subscriber additions at 4-5 lakh. Average revenue per user is expected to decline 1.2 per cent sequentially or stay flat given fewer days in the quarter.Despite the lower ARPU, operating profit is expected to be maintained given flattish content costs. ARPUs have been on an uptrend over the last year moving up from Rs 166 at the end of FY14 to an estimated Rs 177 in FY15, a growth of 6.6 per cent. Ebidta margins are expected to move up from 22.7 per cent in FY14 to about 24.9 in FY15.About 90 per cent of analysts covering the stock have a buy with a target price of Rs 100 which offers over 20 per cent returns from the current levels of about Rs 78.55.

